body: "# Semgrep finding import\n\nSemgrep finding id: 874840463\nRule: javascript.lang.security.audit.detect-non-literal-regexp.detect-non-literal-regexp\nProduct: Code\nSeverity: Medium\nStatus: Open\nConfidence: Low\nCategory: security\nIs Pro Rule: True\nSemgrep autotriage result: Untriaged\nSemgrep file risk tag: Developer Scripts\nRepository: unbraind/pm-cli\nBranch: refs/heads/main\nCreated at: 2026-07-03 12:04:25.346414\nLast opened at: 2026-07-03 12:04:25.327959\n\nLinks:\n- Code: https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli/blob/6f511706628f18743a00a1cfe851e8d1f492684e/src/cli/commands/test.ts#L1506\n- Semgrep: https://semgrep.dev/orgs/unbrained/findings/874840463\n- Repository: https://github.com/unbraind/pm-cli\n\nRule description:\nRegExp() called with a `params` function argument, this might allow an attacker to cause a Regular Expression Denial-of-Service (ReDoS) within your application as RegExP blocks the main thread. For this reason, it is recommended to use hardcoded regexes instead. If your regex is run on user-controlled input, consider performing input validation or use a regex checking/sanitization library such as https://www.npmjs.com/package/recheck to verify that the regex does not appear vulnerable to ReDoS.\n\nImported from downloaded CSV:\nSemgrep_Code_Combined_Findings_2026_07_06.csv (local download, not committed)"
